            <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">The
            Research Book can be purchased on your class local guild.&nbsp; It
            is the item you will use to combine the components to create a new
            spell.&nbsp; Components are found with creatures all over
            Norrath.&nbsp; It is only by adventuring that a player will get the
            components he/she needs.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font color="#004242" size="2" face="Tahoma"><b>Finding
            Components</b></font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">When
            hunting for components, you should know that they will drop from
            creatures of a similar level.&nbsp; For example, if you want to
            research a level 20 spell, you will need level 20 components.&nbsp;
            To find them, you will need to hunt creatures that range from level
            20 to 23.&nbsp; Any creature below level 20 or above level 23 will
            drop Words that are either level 16 or 24.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">Components
            are randomly dropped.&nbsp; There is no specific zone or creature
            that will drop them more often.&nbsp; You just need to be lucky
            enough to kill the mob that drops it.&nbsp; Nevertheless, since the
            level range applies, it is a good idea to hunt in a zone where the
            majority of creatures will be of the level of the component you are
            looking for.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">Components
            can also be purchased from other players and, on occasion, from
            vendor NPCs.&nbsp; Purchasing from NPCs is not uncommon since a
            class can only research spells from that particular class.&nbsp; A
            Necromancer cannot research Enchanter spells for example, even with
            the right components and research book.&nbsp; Thus, players will
            often sell research components that are not particular to that class
            or components they don't need anymore.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font color="#004242" size="2" face="Tahoma"><b>Learning
            the Research Skill</b></font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">Research
            is not a difficult skill to master, but it can be a very painful
            one.&nbsp; The most powerful spells will require components that are
            not easily obtained.&nbsp; As such, you certainly don't want to fail
            when trying to research a high level spell and have to go look for
            the required components all over again.&nbsp; To minimize the
            chances that this will happen, it is recommended that you spend
            practice points in your research skill.&nbsp; Unlike other trade
            skills, you can spend more than 20 points in your research
            skill.&nbsp; It is only limited by the level you currently
            are.&nbsp; As you reach the next spell circle (the level at which
            you gain access to new spells), your research cap will be
            raised.&nbsp; So if you wish to be a master researcher, make sure
            you spend all the practice points you can in your research skill.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">At
            earlier levels, you can also do the <b>Concordance of Research
            quests</b> to increase your research skill without wasting practice
            points in it.&nbsp; These quests are divided for good and evil
            races.</font>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">The
                quest for good races starts in North Karana with the NPC named
                Mrysila, located at -670 -160</font></li>
              <li>
                <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">The
                quest for evil races starts in South Ro, with the NPCs named
                Smith Tv'ysa, located in a small merchant camp at +100 +500</font></li>
            </ul>
            <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">The
            goal of these quests is to obtain simple items that when combined
            will create practice runes.&nbsp; These runes will then be combined
            to gain research skill.&nbsp; There are two major advantages of
            doing these quests.&nbsp; You can gain research skill without using
            practice points and without losing the true research components.</font></p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;</p>
            <p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font color="#004242" size="2" face="Tahoma"><b>Creating
            your First Spell</b></font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">So,
            you obtained the components you need, bought the Research book and
            want to attempt your first research?&nbsp; Well, it is easy
            enough.&nbsp; Simply put the components in your research book and
            hit the combine button.&nbsp; Either if you succeed or fail, the
            components will be lost.&nbsp; If you succeed, you will get a new
            spell.&nbsp; Note that you can only research one spell at a time and
            you should never stack items.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">Failing
            a research is quite common.&nbsp; Your research skill will only
            become more reliable if you are trying to research a spell that is
            from a spell circle below your current one.&nbsp; If you really want
            a spell, have the necessary components, but fear you might fail, it
            might be a good idea to ask a higher level friend of your same class
            that has a better research skill than yours to try it for you.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left"><font size="2" face="Tahoma">A
            last note about research.&nbsp; Intelligence or Wisdom will help you
            succeed more often and learn the research skill faster.&nbsp;
            Whichever attribute is higher for you will determine the one used
            when running the fail/learn check.</font><p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0" align="left">&nbsp;<p style="text-indent: 0; line-height: 100%; word-spacing: 0; margin: 0"><font color="#004242" size="2" face="Tahoma"><b>Spell
            Recipes</b></font>
